Literature Review

The issue of rising sea levels and water scarcity that are plaguing growing communities are ones that must be addressed in the coming decades, and just how to combat them will be an issue of contention. An interesting technology that some countries believe can solve both problems are desalination facilities. These plants take sea water and detoxify it for human use and consumption. Moving forward, the question of how efficient they actually are is vital. The first paper I looked at to answer the question of efficacy focused on Israel, and aimed to ask about the effectiveness of water desalination plants there (Becker, 2011). It first asks, what are direct and indirect external costs of desalination plants for the country. Since there are many ways to address water scarcity, they wanted to understand what the overall impacts of these facilities comes to be. Second, they tackle whether or not other alternatives to water mitigation might not be more viable. They look at three alternatives, increasing wastewater capture and reuse, promotion of water saving technology, and water reduction for agricultural endeavors. The empirical approaches taken are that external costs of desalination plants along coastlines in Israel can be expressed with an equation of C = ( AV*DP)/Q. In this equation, the dependent variable, C is cost per cubic meter of water the plant produces. The independent variables are represented by AV, for average monetary value of Israeli coastline property per unit area, DP, the coastline area taken by desalination plants, and Q, the quantity of desalinated water in cubic meters. The researchers also used a semi-logarithmic function, P =16.11 2.394 ln(W), to express demand for water in Israel, where P is the price of water, and W is the amount of water used in million cubic meters (MCM).
A challenge faced by the researcher was coming up with costs of negative externalities to habitats surrounding areas of these facilities. Desalination plants suck in massive amounts of water and in doing so bring in marine life as well as alter their habitits. Since it is difficult to account for damage to the natural habitats, they were unable to estimate the full effects. The ultimate findings were that desalination plants were too cost ineffective to be viable. They suggested Israel postpone further development of these plants along their coastline and instead shift to water saving and wastewater treatment alternatives which have fewer negative externalities and are less expensive. They believe desalination plants should be reassessed at a future date (ten years in the future they suggest) when technology may be more efficient and safer for the production level Israel is looking for from them. The second research paper (Al Ashry, 2015), looks at the three main types of desalination plants and does a cost-benefit analysis of each type. It aims to understand the economic efficiency of nuclear, gas, and solar desalination plants, and ultimately pick the strongest option. In exploring different energy sources for desalination plants, the researcher uses a number of equations to understand the cost-benefit of each type of plant. They use a first-order autoregressive model to estimate revenues from each of three types of plants, an equation to test the stability and deviation of the explained and unexplained variation in the autoregressive model between actual and estimated variance, then they use a variance ratio to test for the random walk hypothesis, and finally, they employ a heteroscedasticity asymptotic variance to test for consistency.
The author came across challenges incorporating solar radiation in different nations. This may have affected the accuracy of their calculations on impacts of solar power desalination plants in different hemispheres with varying amounts of sunlight. The paper comes to a similar conclusion as the first. Although it appeals to peoples futuristic mindsets, at the moment desalination plants are not as beneficial as we would like them to be. They find that of the three options gas, nuclear, or solar plants, solar seems to be the best due to ease of construction and maintenance.
This literature has changed my view of the question I initially asked, as to whether desalination plants are a worthwhile investment to address rising sea levels, in that it appears the academic community is in agreement that, at the moment, they are not. The current cost, externalities, and capacity of these facilities seem to out way their benefit to communities they aim to serve. Moving forward I believe I will alter my question to what financial alterations would have to happen to make solar powered desalination plants a viable option for coastal regions. To collect data for my altered topic of research I will need to focus my research on solar powered desalination plants. I will aim to collect their cost, maintenance, and output, as well as estimated externalities to local areas to better understand what their impacts are, and what is needed to offset these.

Reference:

  1. Al Ashry, Mohammed. Large Scale Desalination: A Comparative Cost Affective Economic Analyses of Nuclear, Gas and Solar Powered Plants. Theoretical Economics Letters, vol.01, no. 05, 2015, pp.103113, 10.4236/tel.2015.51015.

  2. Becker, Nir. Is Desalination the Most Sustainable Alternative for Water-Shortage Mitigation in Israel? International Journal of Sustainable Economy, vol.3, no. 4, Jan.2011, pp.410424, 10.1504/IJSE.2011.042796.

Data Choice

I had difficulty finding a data set with useful data on the topic of desalination plants and their benefits to regions they are operating in. Due to the construction costs and efficiency of these sites, those companies that install them do not like to give out information so the closest I could find to data on these sites was location based, and only gave categorical and qualitative data.

Since we can not run regression on categorical variables I will be relying on the data set related to vicinity to an incinerator plant, kielmc to run theoretical regressions and tests. Upon analysis of the data only minor cleaning and processing needs to be done prior to testing. This will serve as way to analyze how price of homes flucuate in response to variables, some of which relate to vicinity towards processing plants.

Simple Regression Models log(price) = b0 + b1 + u In this starting simple regression model, log(price) is the dependent variable, and is the log price that the house in the data set sold for. The following regressions will perform t-tests on selected variables at the 95% confidence interval that the variables are statistically signifcant and test the the null hypothesis, H0=B1=0, and the alternative hypothesis H0=B1 not equal to 0.

For my first t-test, at a 95% confidence interval, I found evidence to reject the null hypothesis, since 5.3 > 1.976 and conclude that dist (distance in feet from the incinerator) is a statistically significant determinant of log(price).

For my second t-test, at a 95% confidence interval, I found strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis, since 10.13 > 1.976 and conclude that rooms (number of rooms in the house) is a statistically significant determinant to log(price).

For my third t-test, at a 95% confidence interval, I found evidence to reject the null hypothesis, since -7.82 < -1.976 and conclude that age (age of home) is a statistically significant determinant to log(price).

For my final t-test, at a 95% confidence interval, I found evidence to reject the null hypothesis, since 3.77 > 1.976 and conclude that land (square footage of the lot the house is on) is a statistically significant determinant to log(price).

I chose these four variables to run my initial tests on due to my anticipation that I would see statistically significant correlations between each of the variables and the dependent variable. I was correct in my assumption of dist, rooms, age, and land being influential on price. I tried to choose variables that represented different aspects of the house that would impact price, size, location, age, and amenities.

Heteroskedasticity

#Eye-Ball Test
reg_eb <- lm(price ~ area, data=df)
df$uhat2 <- reg_eb$residuals^2
plot(df$area, df$uhat2)

Based on the error variance there appears to be heteroskedasticity.

#Breusch-Pagan Test
library(lmtest)
## Loading required package: zoo
## 
## Attaching package: 'zoo'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     as.Date, as.Date.numeric
bptest(price ~ log(dist) + log(area) + rooms + baths + age, data=df)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  price ~ log(dist) + log(area) + rooms + baths + age
## BP = 31.623, df = 5, p-value = 7.056e-06

With a LM test stat of 31.62 and a small p-value (7.056e-06) we can reject the null and conclude heteroskedasticity.

bptest(log(price) ~ log(dist) + log(area) + rooms + baths + age, data=df)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  log(price) ~ log(dist) + log(area) + rooms + baths + age
## BP = 9.3886, df = 5, p-value = 0.09453

Though heteroskedasticity still exists in the model it has dropped significantly (from 31.85 to 14.21) by taking the log of price. This makes sense theoretically in that price can scale to large amounts while many stay in a similar range.

Other Issues

There is likely other issues with the model that our regression does not account for. Omitted variables may be adding to the heteroskedasticity we see since the error term is absorbing these variables we are not including in the model. Some examples could be distance from the nearest shopping center, density of neighborhoods, or relation to nearest schools, to name a few. These could be impacting price more than is captured by our current model. Another potential problem with our model could be multicollinearity, though we tried to account for this with a joint significance test of two like variables (rooms and bathrooms). Multicollinearity occurs when two or more variables affect the dependent variable in the same way. There may be some collinearity between distance and area if there are larger houses built away from the incinerator plant as can expected in affluent neighborhoods.

Conclusions

We have strong evidence that the variables representing distance from the incinerator (logged due to scaling as log(dist)), area of the land (logged due to scaling as log(area)), number of bedrooms, number of bathrooms, and the age of the house are all significant indicators of price the house sold for. There appears some heteroskedasticity based on the Bruesch-Pagan test, but was greatly reduced by taking the log of price. This heteroskedasticity may be due to scaling issues, omitted variables, or issues with auto regressive conditional heteroskedasticity, though all these were attempted to account for as best as possible. Endogeneity bias may also play a factor in the model since explanatory variables affecting price may be related as described previously. The distance from the incinerator may also be correlated to the size of the plot the house is built on since wealthy people tend to have large plots of land farther away from processing plants. Also bathrooms and bedrooms tend to be correlated as more bedrooms implies more people and thus a need for more bathrooms.

A potential interpretation of these finding as they relate back to my original research topic idea on desalination plants could be recommendation for policy makers. The results of the regression show a positive affect of distance away from processing plants (an incineration plant in the case of the data) on the price of houses. In order to address this potential issue it would be advantageous to consider installation of these facilities further away from populations as to not affect their house prices. We know there are countless cases of governments placing facilities that are less desirable in areas where people have less resources to push against policies that may harm them. In the case of an incinerator possibly negatively affecting air quality or a desalination plant affecting the ecosystem of the surrounding area, these facilities should be implemented with those marginalized individuals in mind. As evident in the regression, larger plot sizes increase price, so it may be equitable for policy makers to consider placing these facilities near individuals with more relative land than those with less.
